## Layer Details

### Layer 1: `movie_entity.parquet` — Master Table

**Source:** IMDb `title.basics.tsv` (12,336,661 total titles)

| Step | Result |
|------|--------|
| Filter `titleType == "movie"` + non-adult | **730,319 movies** |
| Merge IMDb ratings | 335,434 rated (45.9%) |
| Cross-ref TMDB IDs | 347,413 matched (47.6%) |
| Cross-ref MovieLens IDs | 71,337 matched (9.8%) |

**Schema:** `imdb_id` (PK), `title`, `year`, `runtime`, `genres`, `imdb_rating`, `imdb_votes`, `tmdb_id`, `movielens_id`

---

### Layer 2: `metadata_layer.parquet` — TMDB Enrichment

**Source:** TMDB v11 (654,915 rows with imdb_id)  
**Join:** `tmdb.imdb_id → movie_entity.imdb_id` (inner join)  
**Result:** **347,413 movies** with rich metadata

**Schema:** `imdb_id`, `tmdb_id`, `title`, `overview`, `popularity`, `vote_average`, `vote_count`, `tagline`, `budget`, `revenue`, `poster_path`, `keywords`, `production_companies`, `spoken_languages`, `original_language`, `release_date`, `status`

> **RAG Value:** The `overview` and `keywords` fields are prime candidates for vector embedding.

---

### Layer 3: `plot_layer.parquet` — Wikipedia Plots

**Source:** Wikipedia movie plots (34,886 entries)  
**Mapping:** Title + Year exact match against movie_entity lookup dictionary  
**Result:** **29,724 matched (85.2%)**, 5,162 unmatched

**Schema:** `imdb_id`, `plot_text`, `source`, `origin_ethnicity`, `director`, `cast`, `genre`, `wiki_page`

> **RAG Value:** `plot_text` is the richest free-text field — full plot summaries averaging hundreds of words. Ideal for chunked embedding.

---

### Layer 4: `review_layer.parquet` — Rotten Tomatoes Reviews

**Source:** RT movies (142,891) + RT reviews (1,049,534)

| Step | Result |
|------|--------|
| RT movies → IMDb ID match | **107,064 matched (74.9%)** |
| Reviews joined via RT slug | **926,830 reviews** with text > 20 chars |

**Schema:** `imdb_id`, `rt_id`, `critic_name`, `review_text`, `sentiment`, `score`, `is_top_critic`, `review_state`

> **RAG Value:** `review_text` provides diverse critical perspectives. The `sentiment` field enables sentiment-filtered retrieval.

---

### Layer 5: `recommendation_layer.parquet` — MovieLens Ratings & Tags

**Source:** ML-32M (32,000,204 ratings + 2,000,072 tags)  
**Strategy:** Chunked aggregation — 32M individual ratings aggregated to per-movie stats

| Step | Result |
|------|--------|
| Movies with ratings | **84,432** |
| Movies with tags | **51,323** |
| Combined output | **87,585 movies** |

**Schema:** `imdb_id`, `movielens_id`, `ml_avg_rating`, `ml_rating_count`, `ml_tags` (pipe-separated top 20), `ml_tag_count`

> **RAG Value:** `ml_tags` provides user-generated semantic descriptors (e.g. "atmospheric", "plot twist"). Useful for similarity and recommendation queries.

---

### Layer 6: `regional_layer.parquet` — Indian Cinema

**Source:** Indian movies dataset (50,602 films)  
**Mapping:** `ID` column is already IMDb `tconst` format — direct mapping

**Schema:** `imdb_id`, `title`, `year`, `language`, `region`, `rating`, `votes`, `genre`, `source`

> **RAG Value:** Enables language-filtered queries (Tamil, Hindi, Malayalam, etc.) and regional cinema analysis.

---

### Layer 7: `analysis_layer` — Web Scraping (Placeholder)

**Status:** ⏳ Schema defined, awaiting scraping pipeline

**Target sources:**
- BFI (British Film Institute) — Film theory
- Senses of Cinema — Director analysis
- Bright Lights Film Journal — Film analysis
- Film Companion — Regional film reviews

**Expected output:** 20K–80K articles → JSONL format → each article mapped to `imdb_id` via NER + fuzzy matching

**Schema:** Defined in `rag/processed_dataset/analysis_layer_schema.json`

```json
{
  "source": "BFI",
  "knowledge_type": "film_theory",
  "title": "The Cinematic Language of Kubrick",
  "author": "John Doe",
  "entities": {"directors": [...], "films": [...]},
  "imdb_ids": ["tt0062622"],
  "text": "...article content...",
  "chunks": ["...400-600 token segments..."],
  "url": "https://..."
}
```

> When the scraping pipeline runs, it should output to `rag/scraped_articles/analysis_layer.jsonl` and use the `movie_entity.parquet` lookup table for entity→imdb_id resolution.

